{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17595356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17595356"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:03:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.13,0.22,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67139"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8044"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19534"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19538"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22466"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67139"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EWilson\u0027s disease is an autosomal recessive disorder of copper metabolism that results in copper accumulation in various tissues, particularly the liver and brain. A particular supplement can be used to reduce the absorption of copper.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following supplements could be used?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Calcium","Iron","Magnesium","Selenium","Zinc"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZinc\u003C/strong\u003E supplementation is a key treatment for Wilson\u0027s disease. Zinc acts by inducing intestinal metallothionein, which binds to copper and prevents its absorption. It also reduces copper toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe other supplements listed - \u003Cstrong\u003Eiron\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eselenium\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Emagnesium\u003C/strong\u003E - are not specifically used to treat Wilson\u0027s disease. The main treatments include:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003ECopper chelating agents (penicillamine, trientine)\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EZinc supplementation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EDietary copper restriction\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003EAvoiding copper-rich foods like shellfish, nuts, and chocolate\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Wilson\u0027s disease is treated with copper chelating agents and zinc to reduce copper absorption","Dietary copper restriction is part of Wilson\u0027s disease management","Penicillamine and trientine are copper chelating agents used in Wilson\u0027s disease"],"references":["Mulligan C, Bronstein JM. Wilson Disease: An Overview and Approach to Management. Neurol Clin. 2020 May;38(2):417-432. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2020.01.005. Epub 2020 Feb 28. PMID: 32279718.","Immergluck J, Anilkumar AC. Wilson Disease. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441990/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastr